-- South African Equities: Gold Reef Resorts, Mondi, Naspers, PPC
-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 2011-02-10T12:09:27Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-10/south-african-stocks-fall-for-fourth-day-drdgold-mondi-plc-naspers-move.html
  South Africa ’s FTSE/JSE  Africa  All
Share Index dropped the most since Jan. 31, a fourth day of
losses, declining 295.53, or 0.9 percent, to 32,382.03 at 1:56
p.m. in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.    Gold Reef Resorts Ltd . (GDF SJ), a casino and gaming
company, declined as much as 7.6 percent, before trading 90
cents, or 5.1 percent lower, at 16.80 rand. The company
yesterday concluded its legal arguments in favor of its proposed
merger with Tsogo Sun Holdings at the Competition Tribunal,
which is expected to make its ruling by early next week.  Mondi Group Plc (MNP SJ),  Europe ’s largest maker of office
paper, rose as much as 3.7 percent to 61.89 rand, the highest
since Feb. 7, before trading 1.62 rand, or 2.7 percent higher,
at 61.32 rand. The company said it will post earnings per share
of between 42 euro cents ($0.57) and 49 cents in the year
through December from a loss of 6.5 cents.    Naspers Ltd . (NPN SJ), Africa’s biggest media company,
declined the most since Jan. 28, losing 7.83 rand, or 2 percent,
to 387.16 rand.  Tencent Holdings Ltd ., which is 35 percent owned
by Naspers and is China’s largest Internet company by market
value, retreated 1.8 percent, falling to the lowest in a month
in Hong Kong trading. Emerging-market stocks fell to the lowest
intraday level since Dec. 1 on concern U.S. unemployment and  China ’s efforts to tame inflation will slow the global recovery.  Pretoria Portland Cement Co. (PPC SJ), Africa’s largest
cement producer, dropped to the lowest intraday level since
Sept. 10, losing 69 cents, or 2.3 percent, to 29.15 rand. South
African cement sales declined 4.6 percent to 641,860 metric tons
in January compared with a year earlier, the Cement & Concrete
Institute said in an e-mailed statement today. Last month had
one more sales day than January last year, which, if taken into
account, means sales fell by 9.1 percent, the institute said.  To contact the reporter on this story:
